ence, scope, and scale of contemporary forms of pilgrimage and pilgrimage-related activity. It shows that we need to reflect on how pilgrimage sites, journeys, rituals, stories, and metaphors are entangled with each other and with wider aspects of people’s lives, ranging from an action as trivial as a stroll down the street to the magnitude of forced migration to another country or continent. Offering a new theoretical lexicon and framework for exploring human pilgrimage, Powers of Pilgrimage presents a broad overview of how we can understand pilgrimage activity and proposes that it should be understood not solely as going to, staying at, and leaving a sacred place, but also as occurring in ordinary times, places, and practices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh  aAnglo-Catholic.  aAnn Gold.  aAnna Tsing.  aArnold van Gennep.  aBirthright pilgrimages.  aCamino.  aCatholicism.  aDe Certeau.  aEdith Turner.  aEmile Durkheim.  aEuropean pilgrimage.  aGlenn Bowman.  aHajj.  aHillary Kaell.  aJames Clifford.  aJill Dubisch.  aJohn Eade.  aMaurice Bloch.  aMax Gluckman.  aMecca.  aMedjugorje.  aMichael Sallnow.  aOur Lady of Charity.  aPentecostalism.  aPuri.  aSantiago de Compostela.  aStuart Hall.  aSurinder Bhardwaj.  aThomas Tweed.  aVictor Turner.  aVirgin Mary.  aWalsingham.  aanti-structure.  aarticulation.  aauthenticity.  aboundary object.  acathedrals.  acommunitas.  acontestation.  adiaspora.  aenclave.  aentrainment.  aevangelical Christians.  afriction.  aglobalization.  aheritage.  ajourneys.  alandscape.  alaterality.  aliminality.  amemory.  amigration.  amulti-sited.  anarrative.  anarratives.  apalimpsest.  apenumbra.  apilgrimage.  apolitical economy.